T1  - Tax analysis in a real-business-cycle model: On measuring Harberger triangles and Okun gaps
AU  - Greenwood, Jeremy
AU  - Huffman, Gregory W.
JO  - Journal of Monetary Economics
VL  - 27
IS  - 2
SP  - 167
EP  - 190
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/04/01/
SN  - 0304-3932
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3932(91)90040-U
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030439329190040U
AB  - A tax-distorted real-business-cycle model is parameterized, calibrated, and solved numerically in an attempt to measure the size of Harberger Triangles relative to Okun Gaps. In particular, the model constructed is used to study, quantitatively, the impact of various distortional government tax and subsidy schemes. It is shown that the government can use tax policy to stabilize cyclical fluctuations, and this is done for the economy being studied. The benefits of implementing such a stabilization policy are calculated and compared with the size of the welfare gains realized from reducing various tax distortions.
